  "abstract": "Downy mildew (DM) caused by Sclerospora graminicola\r\nis prevalent in most pearl millet (Pennisetum glaucum)\r\ngrowing parts of the semi-arid tropics. The pathogen is an\r\nobligate oomycetes and reproduces both by sexual and\r\nasexual processes. Heterothallism and sexual cross\r\ncompatibility among the isolates of S. graminicola\r\n(Michelmore et al. 1982, Thakur et al. 2004, Pushpavathi\r\net al. 2006a) lead to genetic and pathogenic variability in\r\nthe pathogen population. Sporangia, the asexual spores,\r\nproduced on the infected leaves help in secondary spread\r\nof the disease. In India, the disease is quite severe on\r\nsingle-cross F1 hybrids and causes substantial yield losses\r\n(Singh 1995, Thakur et al. 2003).",
